{{Italic title}} '''''Dead Sea Scrolls: Life and Faith in Ancient Times''''', also known as '''Dead Sea Scrolls: The Exhibition''', is a [[travelling exhibition]] of artifacts from the [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|ancient Kingdoms of Israel and Judah]], including a select number of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]]. The exhibition was created by the [[Israel Antiquities Authority]] with items from the Israel National Treasures Department, and was produced by [[Discovery Times Square Exposition|Discovery Times Square]] and the [[Franklin Institute]]. The exhibition claims to be the largest display of ancient Israeli artifacts ever displayed outside of [[Israel]].
==Tour history== The exhibition first opened in New York City on October 28, 2011, under the title ''Dead Sea Scrolls: Life and Faith in Biblical Times''.<ref name="premiere_press_release">{{cite press release |title=Dead Sea Scrolls: Life and Faith in Biblical Times Exhibition to make world premiere at Discovery Times Square in October |date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=MWW Group |location=New York |url=http://www.discoverytsx.com/userfiles/file/pdf/Dead%20Sea%20Scrolls/Dead%20Sea%20Scrolls%20Announcement%20Press%20Release%20FINAL%209_16_11.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=April 25, 2013 |ref= }}</ref> It is curated by Dr. Risa Levitt Kohn of San Diego State University, and Debora Ben Ami of the Israel Antiquities Authority.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Brings to Life the Greatest Archeological Discovery of the 20th Century Taking Visitors Back 2,000 Years |date=February 27, 2012 |publisher=Museum of Science, Boston |location=Boston |url=http://www.mos.org/node/352941 |accessdate=April 25, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503010906/http://www.mos.org/node/352941 |archivedate=May 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
==On display== The exhibition features twenty of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]], displayed ten at a time. About 600 artifacts from the [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|ancient Kingdoms of Israel and Judah]] are also displayed, including a stone block from the [[Western Wall]] of [[Jerusalem]]'s [[Temple Mount]].<ref name="premiere_press_release"/>
